** Regarding data serialization handlers for linguistics
	- Perhaps to MySQL, JSON
	- Not sure how Boost::Serialization provides serialization in XML;
	  is it possible to hard-wire the XML data syntax (see following examples)
	- A bit of perfection is needed for the LocalLexical class; should be able to read this format:
		> SYMBOL
		> SEMANTIC_UUID_0 FLAGS_0
		> SEMANTIC_UUID_1 FLAGS_1
		>           ....
		> SEMANTIC_UUID_n FLAGS_n
	  Using a similar syntax as displayed above for XML;
		> <Lexical symbol="SYMBOL">
		> 	<Flag semantic="SEMANTIC_UUID_0" set="FLAGS_0" />
		> 	<Flag semantic="SEMANTIC_UUID_1" set="FLAGS_0" />
		>				.....
		>	<Flag semantic="SEMANTIC_UUID_n" set="FLAGS_n" />
	 And another for JSON;
		> {
		>	symbol : "SYMBOL",
		>	flags : {
		>		"SEMANTIC_UUID_0" : "FLAGS_0"
		>		"SEMANTIC_UUID_1" : "FLAGS_1"
		>			  ..........
		>		"SEMANTIC_UUID_n" : "FLAGS_n"
		>	}
		> }

** Correct errors over files.

** Add remote support for downloading/accessing new sects of data for the
	ontology and linguistics. The URI for accessing such information
	can be set up at: << http://www.thesii.org/projects/wintermute/data.php?src=DATA_SRC >>
	where DATA_SRC is either 'onto' or 'ling'.

   - Obtaining information in XML:  (data.php?fmt=xml)
   			 .. JSON   (data.php?fmt=json)
			 .. MySQL  (data.php?fmt=mysql)

   - Obtaining via UUID: 
	> (data.php?fmt=xml&uuid=393-2434-2323-232323-34324234&src=onto)
	  Gets an entry from the ontology in XML format (in OWL syntax).

	> (data.php?fmt=json&uuid=34-34324-324234-232323232-2323&src=ling&lcl=en)
	  Gets an entry from the English linguistics information repository (in JSON format).

	> (data.php?fmt=mysql&uuid=dump&src=onto)
	  Dumps all of the information stored on the server in the ontology repository (in a MySQL query format).

** Allow an abstract class manage (should be Wintermute::Data::Statistics):
	- number of known concepts (ontology) or words (linguistics)
	- keep track of most used concepts and words
	- (using Boost::Graph or other system) generate graphical information about usage
	- allow chronological, conditional, or manual backups of data to be formed.
	- (optional) permit caching of online resources used by system.
